      {
        "id": 4403284,
        "name": "Todd Tucker",
        "username": "Todd_Tucker",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/todd_tucker/{size}/76924_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-06-29T00:24:15.885Z",
        "cooked": "<p>A few wines from the last month.</p>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=819352\"><b>2008 Hubert Lamy Saint-Aubin 1er Cru En Remilly Blanc</b></a> - France, Burgundy, C\u00f4te de Beaune, Saint-Aubin 1er Cru (6/8/2024)<br>\n<p>Pop and pour. Drunk over an evening with one glass left for  the following day.<br>\nLovely maturing nose. nutty with orchard fruit, chalk, lemon curd, and jasmine. Chiseled and structured yet seemingly only midweighted. Fresh, deep, and detailed with terrific blend of intensity with lift. Above all this is harmonious. Effortlessly beautiful wine drinking at peak. Delicious.</p>\n<p>FWIW, the leftover glass lot day 2 ost a touch of its magic.<b>(95 points)</b></p></li><p></p>\n\n<p>Posted from <a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com\">CellarTracker</a></p>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=2216639\"><b>2014 Hubert Lamy Saint-Aubin 1er Cru Les Murgers des Dents de Chien Blanc</b></a> - France, Burgundy, C\u00f4te de Beaune, Saint-Aubin 1er Cru (6/19/2024)<br>\nPop and pour. Drunk over an evening.<br><br>This wine keeps getting better. A terrific nose that takes you to the mother rock. The matchstick of earlier bottles has faded. Asian pear, chalk, some lemon curd, and florals with a touch of maturing nuttiness more than the bitter almond of the last couple bottles. The wood's fully integrated and it is hitting its stride. Deep, structured, and toothsome on the palate with terrific extract and a sense of precision and focused power. That said, this is not about power, but rather harmony. Everything is in place. A fantastic summation of soil, acid fruit and florals. It feels like drinking mineral water made form Chardonnay grapes. Drinking at early peak now. I love Hubert Lamy's wines, and this is a belter. Terrific. 94 and I might be being stingy. <b>(94 points)</b></li>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=661623\"><b>2007 Domaine Dujac Chambolle-Musigny</b></a> - France, Burgundy, C\u00f4te de Nuits, Chambolle-Musigny (6/21/2024)<br>\nPop and pour. Some decanted and some drunk from the glass slowly over several hours as it opened <br><br>At first pretty awkward with some earth, red fruits and savoriness. All elbows and knees, not particularly pleasurable. After an hour or two in the glass and in the decanter it starts to unfurl leaving lovely red fruits, undergrowth, some stemmy  softness and ferrous notes. Midweighted and savory more than fruit driven, with excellent balance and textural softness with fine detail. Over time it fleshes out a bit more gaining good depth for a village wine, more undergrowth and red fruits with some cooling herbal notes from the stem inclusion. By four hours of being open, this was giving a lot. Solid village wine. Give this some air if you drink it now. It really benefitted. 91 once patience was rewarded <b>(91 points)</b></li>\n<p>All of these were showing well, the both the '14 Lamy and the '07 Dujac have a lot left in the tank. I adore the '08 En Remilly and am sad to be down to my last couple bottles of a case. It has been consistently terrific for years, but I would consider drinking them if you have them. I can\u2019t imagine it showing any better than it is now.</p>\n<p>Thank for reading.</p></ul>",
